72
00:02:49,025 --> 00:02:53,207
and we can't contractually launch on Steam until it's done.

73
00:02:53,207 --> 00:02:53,768
So we're waiting.

74
00:02:53,768 --> 00:02:58,410
Three years of game development, climaxing in an upload progress bar.

75
00:02:58,410 --> 00:02:59,491
How did this happen?

76
00:02:59,491 --> 00:03:01,392
We're three hours late, and our backers are tweeting.

77
00:03:01,392 --> 00:03:01,772
Fuck.

78
00:03:01,772 --> 00:03:02,392
Fuck, fuck, fuck.

79
00:03:02,392 --> 00:03:03,013
Why is it so tight?

80
00:03:03,013 --> 00:03:05,174
Well, it's always tight, isn't it?

81
00:03:05,174 --> 00:03:08,396
When you make a schedule for your game,

82
00:03:08,396 --> 00:03:10,737
you fill that schedule with the things you want to put into it,

83
00:03:10,737 --> 00:03:13,238
because you will always want more things than you can have.

84
00:03:14,309 --> 00:03:17,972
So you just accept that, set a release date, and work backwards.

85
00:03:17,972 --> 00:03:20,333
A lot of things at the end are polish.

86
00:03:20,333 --> 00:03:23,395
Polish is complicated. Yo, let's talk about it.

87
00:03:23,395 --> 00:03:27,017
Polish is not always the right priority.

88
00:03:27,017 --> 00:03:29,519
We love polish in games because it makes them shine.

89
00:03:29,519 --> 00:03:33,362
Playtesting to refine clarity and maintain a flow state for players.

90
00:03:33,362 --> 00:03:36,484
Fixing game-breaking bugs to avoid frustrating crashes.

91
00:03:36,484 --> 00:03:39,566
Iterating on art so that it's at the peak of your craft that you're able to achieve.

92
00:03:39,566 --> 00:03:41,447
Those are all good things, right?

93
00:03:42,248 --> 00:03:49,213
And usually the sign of a game that was planned poorly is glaring lack of polish because they ran out of time.

94
00:03:49,213 --> 00:03:55,097
It looks cheap or glitchy, or the online servers crash, or the difficulty curve has frustrating spikes, or you can get stuck.

95
00:03:55,097 --> 00:03:57,980
Here are a list of games that some of those apply to.

96
00:03:57,980 --> 00:04:00,922
Skyrim, Red Dead Redemption, Hyper Light Drifter.

97
00:04:00,922 --> 00:04:05,205
Respectively, they were glitchy, glitchy, and you can get stuck.

98
00:04:05,205 --> 00:04:07,527
But people kinda like those games.

99
00:04:07,527 --> 00:04:09,088
Maybe not the last one as much.

100
00:04:10,497 --> 00:04:11,738
Here's the truth, you pick your battles.

101
00:04:11,738 --> 00:04:15,801
Just like you can't add every feature, you can't perfect all the polish.

102
00:04:15,801 --> 00:04:18,764
And I'm a proponent of less polish, more love.

103
00:04:18,764 --> 00:04:19,645
Not no polish!

104
00:04:19,645 --> 00:04:21,246
Sloppy craft is bad craft.

105
00:04:21,246 --> 00:04:26,291
Playtest, fix, refine, but keep an eye on what you're giving up with every little piece you polish.

106
00:04:26,291 --> 00:04:28,413
Leave room for the love.

107
00:04:28,413 --> 00:04:31,135
The love, as I call it, is the little things.

108
00:04:31,782 --> 00:04:35,744
touches you want to add for years of production, but you've never had time.

109
00:04:35,744 --> 00:04:38,965
And you won't, unless you take time. There came a moment in our final month when I

110
00:04:38,965 --> 00:04:43,806
had to choose between fixing a rare bug and finally building the Dash Challenge,

111
00:04:43,806 --> 00:04:47,428
a little mini-game inspired by Super Mario RPG that I'd wanted to put in our

112
00:04:47,428 --> 00:04:51,829
game since the beginning. So guess what? The bug stayed and I made the challenge,

113
00:04:51,829 --> 00:04:56,391
and it's the single piece of our game I hear the most about from fans.

114
00:04:56,391 --> 00:04:59,892
Some hate it, some love it, some love to hate it, but they remember it, and no one

115
00:04:59,892 --> 00:05:01,012
has mentioned that bug.

116
00:05:02,297 --> 00:05:04,078
Trade polish for love.

117
00:05:04,078 --> 00:05:06,080
That's what your players will remember.

118
00:05:06,080 --> 00:05:09,603
And what they remember is all that matters.

119
00:05:09,603 --> 00:05:11,344
